# Swift game architecture rules

Applies to Swift source files. Keep games testable, adaptable, and small.

## Separate logic from rendering
- All game **rules and mutable state** live in pure Swift types with **no** `import SwiftUI`
  or `import SpriteKit`. This keeps the model unit-testable without a simulator.
- SwiftUI views and `SKScene`s are **thin**: they bind to the model, render it, and translate
  input into model intents. No game rules in the view/scene.

## State machine
- Use an explicit `enum GameState { case menu, playing, paused, won, lost }`.
- A single controller owns transitions; views derive from it (don't fork state).
- Modern targets: `@Observable` (Observation). Older: `ObservableObject` + `@Published`.

## Modular layout
```
GameName/
├─ App/        Models/        Systems/
├─ Scenes/     Views/         Resources/   Tests/
```
- Many small, single-purpose files over a few large ones.
- Systems are focused (input, score, spawn, collision, audio, save) and independently testable.

## Game loop & time
- Advance by clamped `dt` (e.g. `dt = min(dt, 1/30)`); never tie movement to "per frame".
- SpriteKit: drive the model from `update(_:)`, then mirror model → nodes.
- SwiftUI: prefer state + `withAnimation`; use `TimelineView(.animation)`/`Canvas` only when you
  truly need per-frame rendering.

## Input
- Translate gestures/touches into model **intents**; the model decides legality and scoring.
- Keep hit-testing in the view/scene; keep the verdict in the model.

## Persistence
- Small `Codable` save model in `UserDefaults` or a JSON file; include `schemaVersion`; tolerate
  missing keys. Save only progress/settings — never personal data.

## Assets & dependencies
- No copyrighted assets — placeholder vector shapes / SF Symbols, or user-owned assets only.
- Levels are JSON **data**, not code (see the skill's `assets/level-schema-template.json`).
- Apple frameworks preferred; justify any third-party package.

